occurrences.line_text: That mote the passengers thereto allure;
She did allure with gifts and speaches milde,
Did cast for to allure, into her trap to fall.
Nought vnder heauen so strongly doth allure
The peoples great compassion vnto her allure.
Or to allure such fondlings, whom she trayned
By which he might her to his loue allure,
But when thereto they might not be allured,
That to disloyalty she will not be allured.
That those, whom she to pitie had allured,
Allured be, for prayer nor for meed.
Through false allurement of that pleasing baite,
And all her vaine allurements did forsake,
Then with what sleights and sweet allurements she
And by his false allurements wylie draft
Or to his part allures, and bribeth vnder hand.
And with so firme affection were allyde,
Of such, as vertues like mote vnto him allye.
And noble minds of yore allyed were,
Then Ruddoc and proud Stater, both allyes,
doth sober Alma dwell,
Alma she called was, a virgin bright;
By them as Alma passed with her guestes,
Thence backe againe faire Alma led them right,
Soone as the gracious Alma came in place,
Till Alma him bespake, Why wonder yee
And counselled faire Alma, how to gouerne well.
Whom Alma hauing shewed to her guestes,
But Alma thence the[m] led to th'hindmost roome of three.
Crau'd leaue of Alma, and that aged sire,
Till gentle Alma seeing it so late,
There Alma like a virgin Queene most bright,
The Ferriman, as Alma had behight,
And eke the fairest Alma met him there
Of the faire Alma greatly were procured,
His almes for want of faith he doth accuse;
And godly worke of Almes and charitee
Of which he dealt large almes, as did befall:
As when almightie Ioue in wrathfull mood,
Who life did limit by almightie doome,
Almightie God her gaue such powre, and puissance great.
With his almightie hand, and did it call
Which Merlin made by his almightie art
Which first was spoken by th'Almightie lord,
That euen th'Almightie selfe she did maligne,
As their Almightie maker first ordained,
As where th'Almighties lightning brond does light,
By righteous sentence of th'Almighties law:
With endlesse cost, to be th'Almighties see;
In seate of iudgement, in th'Almighties stead,
Sith in th'Almighties euerlasting seat
Eternall God in his almighty powre,
What haue I, but to praise th'Almighty, that doth send it?
The second was as Almner of the place,
Like to an Almond tree ymounted hye
And almost rent her tender hart in tway;
Him all amazd, and almost made affeard:
That had almost committed crime abhord,
That almost it did haynous violence
The faire Sabrina almost dead with feare,
Belphebe finds him almost dead,
Panting for breath, and almost out of hart,
That almost in the backe he oft her strake:
He fainted, and was almost dead with feare,
Then when the second watch was almost past,
His mighty heart did almost rend in tway,
That almost had against you trespassed this day.
She almost fell againe into a swound,
The other almost dead and desperate
And almost blind through eld, that scarce her way could see.
And almost would his balances haue broken:
Of death, the which them almost ouertooke,
As if the prize she gotten had almost,
For very ruth, which did it almost riue,
So that he now has almost spent his spright.
That with one fall his necke he almost brake,
Was almost dead, misdoubting least of new
That made him almost mad for fell despight.
With which his hideous club aloft he dites,
Forelifting vp aloft his speckled brest,
Then gan he tosse aloft his stretched traine,
When the last deadly smoke aloft did steeme,
To clime aloft, and others to excell:
Or flings aloft, or treads downe in the flore,
That backe againe it did aloft rebownd,
And on the rocke the waues breaking aloft,
And her two lilly paps aloft displayd,
But standing high aloft, low lay thine eare,
Reeking aloft, vprolled to the sky:
As Hellene, when she saw aloft appeare
Nine times he heard him come aloft ere day,
That same aloft he hong in open vew,
And friskt, and flong aloft, and louted low on knee.
At an Herneshaw, that lyes aloft on wing,
Sometimes aloft he layd, sometimes alow;
His dreadfull hand he heaued vp aloft,
But being vp, he lookt againe aloft,
Which doen he gan aloft t'aduance his arme,
Then was she faire alone, when none was faire in place.
Alone he wandring thee too long doth want:
The gentle virgin left behind alone
On top of greene Selinis all alone,
In one alone left hand he now vnites,
Where sate a gentle Lady all alone,
His Palmer now shall foot no more alone:
Wandreth alone with bow and arrowes keene,
Or fly away, or bide alone behind:
Making sweet solace to her selfe alone;
Sitting alone, his bitter lips did bight,
Honour and dignitie from her alone,
Then did he raigne alone, when he none equall knew.
Thus now alone he conquerour remaines;
Vpon a milk-white Palfrey all alone,
But wreake your wrongs wrought to this knight alone,
Is not enough, that I alone doe dye,
Huge hostes of men he could alone dismay,
That through this forest wandreth thus alone;
In this wild forrest wandring all alone,
To be th'ensample of true loue alone,
To saueguard her, ywandred all alone;
Alone he rode without his Paragone;
To the wide world, and let her fly alone,
Straying alone withouten groome or guide;
For he was much affraid, himselfe alone to find.
Lo now the heauens obey to me alone,
On which there stood an Image all alone,
And hard aduentures twixt themselues alone,
Thereat did greatly grudge, that he alone
That chaleng'd ought in Florimell, saue they alone.
That men on him the more might gaze alone.
Sweete is the loue that comes alone with willingnesse.
At last to Braggadochio selfe alone
And now no more for him but I alone,
And spredding ouer all the flore alone,
She syre and mother is her selfe alone,
And let him liue vnlou'd, or loue him selfe alone.
But pyn'd, &; mourn'd, & languisht, and alone did weepe.
But right sate in the middest of the beame alone.
So were they left Lords of the field alone:
Where she might sit nigh to the den alone,
That liues on earth; but vnto those alone
An aged wight, wayfaring all alone,
Whiles she alone is left, and thou here found?
Standing alone on foot, in foule array:
Being vnhable else alone to ride;
But Calepine, now being left alone
He would not suffer her alone to fare,
Why haue ye me alone thus long yleft?
In which he liu'd alone, like carelesse bird in cage.
To heale your selues, and must proceed alone
Now left alone in great extremity,
Would not her leaue alone in her great need.
Whereas his loue was sitting all alone,
Whereas the Prince himselfe lay all alone,
In th'open fields an Infant left alone,
Now seeing Calidore left all alone,
Was she to whom that shepheard pypt alone,
That her alone he for his part desired
But what could he gainst all them doe alone?
But with her went along, as a strong gard
His three deformed heads did lay along,
Drew by the haire along vpon the ground,
He cast him downe to ground, and all along
On euery side they placed were along.
With many raunges reard along the wall;
Which all along the Southerne sea-coast lay,
And the light bubbles daunced all along,
Whose lignage from this Lady I deriue along.
Along the strond, which as she ouer-went,
Along the margent of the fomy shore,
She wounded had, the same along did trace
In endlesse rancks along enraunged were,
Thus as he led the Beast along the way,
And who that was, which chaced her along the lands.
And saw his drouer driue along the streame,
Along the fomy waues driuing his finny droue.
Of wealthy Thamis washed is along,
And flancked both the bridges sides along,
Next these came Tyne, along whose stony bancke
And equitie to measure out along,
His corps was carried downe along the Lee,
So him they led through all their streetes along,
For may no Knight nor Lady passe along
And then to his first quest he passed forth along.
He him preuenting, layes on earth along,
Therewith he mured vp his mouth along,
Then bad the knight his Lady yede aloofe,
But stood aloofe, vnweeting what to doe;
He durst not nigh approch, but kept aloofe,
Who staying nought to question from aloofe,
But kept aloofe for dread to be descryde,
He roar'd aloud, whiles life forsooke his stubborne brest.
From lofty siege began these words aloud to sound.
Then gan the cursed wretch aloud to cry,
Aloud to her he oftentimes did call,
And call aloud for helpe, ere helpe were past;
She heard a shrilling Trompet sound aloud,
They all gan shout aloud, that all the heauen rings.
Then would he laugh aloud, and gather great delight.
He cald to him aloud, his case to rew,
And howld aloud to see his Lord there slaine,
Thereat he shriekt aloud, that with his cry
To whom I cald aloud, halfe angry therewithall.
And now for helpe aloud in earnest cride.
Crying for helpe aloud. But when as ny
Called aloud vnto the watchfull ward,
He brayd aloud for very fell despight;
Gan shout aloud, that vnto heauen it rong;
At him began aloud to barke and bay,
Crying aloud to shew her sad misfare
Gan cry aloud with horrible affright,
She starting vp, began to shrieke aloud,
Then one of them aloud vnto him cryde,
Cryde out aloud for mercie him to saue;
Benumbes her cheekes: Then out aloud she cries,
And shrieke aloud, that with the peoples voyce
Which in their lower braunches sung aloud;
Gan cry to them aloud, to helpe ere all too late.
And gan aloud for Pastorell to call;
Him liberty was left aloud to rore:
With that aloude she gan to bray and yell,
With that aloude the faire Serena cryde
Sometimes aloft he layd, sometimes alow;
But vanisht is. The Elfe him cals alowd,
Loe yonder he, cryde Archimage alowd,
Chaunted alowd their chearefull harmonie:
Did shrieke alowd, that through the house it rong,
And offred that to iustifie alowd.
Swift Rhene, and Alpheus still immaculate:
Alreadie harnessed for iourney new;
Loe, loe alreadie, how the fowles in aire
Whom fortune hath alreadie laid in lowest seat.
Alreadie seemes that fortunes headlong wheele
Being alreadie dead with fearefull fright.
For he already plighted his right hand
For hardly could be hurt, who was already stong.
Already fought, his voyage to pursew.
So her he deemes already but a damned ghoste.
Als Vna earnd her traueill to renew.
Als flew his steed, as he his bands had brast,
Him als accompanyd vpon the way
Als in her lap a louely babe did play
Als when his brother saw the red bloud rayle
Als his faire Leman, flying through a brooke,
Als as she double spake, so heard she double,
As als by this, that now a new debate
Als of his owne rash hand one wound was to be seene.
And glisters wide, as als' of wondrous Bath,
And als' of princely grace to be inclyn'd thereto.
Als at his backe a great wyde net he bore,
Long since had fought in field. Als Claribell
Vpon his shield the like was also scor'd,
But wanting rest will also want of might?
And also nigh consumed is the lingring day.
With drearie shriekes did also her bewray;
There also was king Croesus, that enhaunst
There also was that mightie Monarch layd
Here also sprong that goodly golden fruit,
He also gaue to fugitiues of Spayne,
In which accord the Prince was also plaste,
And also it impregnable did make;
Where also proofe of thy prow valiaunce
Then Griffyth Conan also shall vp reare
That raignest also in the Continent,
Where also many plaints to her were brought,
Mote not mislike you also to abate
And also far vnlike conditions has;
She also dofte her heauy haberieon,
Also to win Deucalions daughter bright,
Those dreadfull flames she also found delayd,
There also was the name of Nimrod strong,
And those same cursed seedes doe also serue
Where I with sound of trompe will also rest a whyle.
Which losse her made like passion also proue.
And also of their priuate loues beguyled;
In entrance, did me also friend in my retrate.
There also some most famous founders were
There also was the wide embayed Mayre,
And also those which wonne in th'azure sky?
That powre he also doth to Princes lend,
And thether also came in open sight
And also of her wound, which sore did paine,
So also did that great Oetean Knight
They also doe by his diuine permission
Though also those mote question'd be aright,
So also did this Monster vse like slight
Them also gan assaile with outrage bold,
He also gan vplooke with drery eye,
And also for the sharpnesse of her rankling wound.
But also trayterously did wound her weary Knight.
To guide mens labours, brought them also ease,
And also of the obiect of his vew,
And also naked are, that without guile
And also of the place, whose pleasures rare
With them also was taken Coridon,
And also all those flockes, which they before
Both loosers lot, and victours prayse alsoe.
There was an Altar built of pretious stone,
Vpon an altar of some costly masse,
And all about her altar scattered lay
That from the Altar all about did blow
Built a faire Chappell, and an Altar framed
Vnder that cursed Idols altar stone;
The Monster vnderneath the Altar lay;
Which like an Altar did it selfe vprere,
In which an altar shortly they erected,
Of few greene turfes an altar soone they fayned,
The Damzell was before the altar set,
Whom by the Altar he doth sitting find,
An Altare, caru'd with cunning imagery,
When morning altars purgd with enemies life,
His cursed hand gainst God, and on his altars daunst.
Witnesse the burning Altars, which he swore,
What heauens? what altars? what enraged heates
Whiles th'altars fume with frankincense arownd,
Altars defyl'd, and holy things defast,
And odours rising from the altars flame.
An hundred Altars round about were set,
And altars vnto him, and temples lent,
And by the altars side her selfe to slumber plaste.
There forth issewd, from vnder th'Altars smooke,
And Altars fouled, and blasphemy spoke,
The substance is not chaunged, nor altered,
Whose liues although decay'd, yet loues decayed neuer.
Her cursed head, although it itched naught;
In which although good Fortune me befall,
Yet would he not him hurt, although he might:
Although Blandina did with all her arts
Although his quest were farre afore him gon;
Knowing his voice although not heard long sin,
Her craftie head was altogether bald,
But chaunged is, and often altred to and fro.
As of humane, that they may altred bee,
Where long remaining, he did alwaies striue
Fro[m] Guendolene his wife, though alwaies faithfull prou'd.
Nothing on earth mote alwaies happie beene.
And so her selfe did alwaies to him tell;
Gainst whom he alwaies bent a brasen shield,
And alwaies in her hand two clewes of silke she twynd.
Was alwaies flitting as the wauering wind,
And with her alwaies ride, till he another get.
But alwaies wept and wailed night and day,
Gainst Blandamour, whom alwaies he enuide:
The same to all stoode alwaies open wide:
But alwaies doe their powre within iust compasse pen.
Mongst which my most delight hath alwaies been,
Of which he grace and glory wonne alwaies,
Of euery blaste, and sayling alwaies on the port.
Therefore they alwaies smoothly seeme to smile,
For the thicke shrubs, which did them alwaies shade
Which from a sacred fountaine welled forth alway.
The baser wit, whose idle thoughts alway
The priuie guilt whereof makes him alway
She alway smyld, and in her hand did hold
Which he in store about him kept alway,
In which old Styx her aged bones alway,
Deawed with siluer drops, that trickled downe alway.
Now ye haue made my heart to wake alway,
But ioyous peace and quietnesse alway,
But that which yeeldeth vertues meed alway?
He foot by foot him followed alway,
And alwayes led, to her with reuerence rare
Did alwayes sore, beating his yron wings;
Thereto the Heauens alwayes Iouiall,
For loue does alwayes bring forth bounteous deeds,
Which alwayes of his paines he made the chiefest meed.
But stretched forth in idlenesse alwayes,
But alwayes did their dread encounter fly:
Yet victors both them selues alwayes esteemed.
Alwayes, to execute her stedfast doome,
But what on earth can alwayes happie stand?
On which his hungry eye was alwayes bent;
Frequented of these gentle Nymphes alwayes,
His target alwayes ouer her pretended;
Am now enforst a far vnfitter taske,
I that do seeme not I, Duessa am,
Am th'only daughter of a King and Queene,
(I witnesse am) in many a cruell fight;
And am I now in safetie sure (quoth he)
I bounden am streight after this emprize,
I witnesse am, and this their wretched sonne,
Then loud he cryde, I am your humble thrall.
His am I Atin, his in wrong and right,
That am the author of this hainous deed,
That am, I weene, most wretched man aliue,
But I, that am fraile flesh and earthly wight,
I Pilate am the falsest Iudge, alas,
Which were it not, that I am else delaid
Pensiue I yeeld I am, and sad in mind,
Or keepe their cabins: much I am affeard,
Thus am I hopelesse euer to attaine
But all my dayes am like to wast in vaine,
Yet am I glad that here I now in safety am.
Yet am I glad that here I now in safety am.
For of her safety in great doubt I am,
If she were thine, and thou as now am I?
Well falles it thee that I am not in plight
Aye me (said she) where am I, or with whom?
In which I daily dying am too long.
To doe her seruice, so as I am bond.
Me iustly terme, that to this shame am brought,
I am adiur'd, best counsell to impart
I am the wrong'd, whom ye did enterprise
Of more reuenge? if more, then I am shee,
Too much am I to blame for that faire Maide,
How cleare I am from blame of this vpbraide:
That oft I driuen am to great distresse,
Which I pursue, of whom I am right glad
Then wote ye that I am a Briton borne,
But I am bound by vow, which I profest
Full loth am I (quoth he) as now at earst,
I am th'vnfortunate Matilde by name,
To whom she thus; I am, as now ye see,
Nor am enuyde of any one therefore;
And when I wearie am, I downe doe lay
The Sarazin this hearing, rose amain,
Of the wide aire her way does cut amaine,
But being past, he thus began amaine;
Her selfe she threw, and teares gan shed amaine;
And eke the breathfull bellowes blew amaine,
A streame of coleblacke bloud thence gusht amaine,
But coucht his speare, and ran at him amaine.
And layd at him amaine with all his will and might.
Let driue at him so dreadfully amaine,
Which when the Lady saw, she cryde amaine;
With his sharpe steele, and ran at him amaine
Sad Amaranthus, made a flowre but late,
Sad Amaranthus, in whose purple gore
And th'amarous sweet spoiles to greedy eyes reuele.
Amased stands, her selfe so mockt to see
Or the blind God, that doth me thus amate,
More lucklesse disauentures did amate:
That cheard his friends, and did his foes amate:
The which them did in modest wise amate,
And safest seemes, him soonest doth amate,
So him he held, and did through might amate:
But in the Porch, that did them sore amate,
That when she saw, it did her much amate,
Did him assayle, and mightily amate,
That all the warders it did sore amate,
But tell, Sir Terpin, ne let you amate
Ye bene right hard amated, gratious Lord,
Stood long amaz'd, as she amated weare.
Findes Mordant and Amauia slaine
Which Mordant and Amauia did rew;
His sea-horses did seeme to sport amayne,
And with the sight amazd, forgat his furious forse.
She more amaz'd, in double dread doth dwell;
But still twixt feare and hope amazd does sit,
Stood long amazd, and burnt in his intent;
And eke the fruitfull-headed beast, amaz'd
Which when the knights beheld, amazd they were,
Him all amazd, and almost made affeard:
Which when the Peasant saw, amazd he stood,
That sonnes of men amazd their sternnesse to behold.
Do greatly stand amaz'd at such vnwonted wonder.
Were much amaz'd the headlesse tronke to see
Stood still amaz'd, holding his idle sweard;
That all men stood amaz'd, & at his might did wonder.
Stood long amaz'd, as she amated weare.
Whereat the knight amaz'd, yet did not rest,
That detestable sight him much amazde,
All in amaze he suddenly vp start
Her glorious glitterand light doth all mens eyes amaze.
And stroue for to amaze the weaker sights;
Ne had one word to speake, for great amaze,
At length they both vpstarted in amaze;
All which by nature made did nature selfe amaze.
Not with amaze, as women wonted bee,
Straunge there to see, it did them much amaze,
These marchants fixed eyes did so amaze,
Their steeds do stagger, and amazed stand,
Then forth they ranne like two amazed deare,
His hastie hand he doth amazed hold,
Their frayle amazed senses did confound:
Th'amazed vulgar tels of warres and mortall fight.
He standes amazed, how he thence should fade.
She greatly grew amazed at the sight,
The trembling ghosts with sad amazed mood,
The Marriner yet halfe amazed stares
All stand amazed at so vncouth sight,
That with your worth the world amazed make,
And all the heauens stood still amazed with his threat.
All in the open hall amazed stood,
Sterne was their looke, like wild amazed steares,
Nigh his wits end then woxe th'amazed knight,
Great Neptune stood amazed at their sight,
So stared he on her, and stood long while amazed.
That wondrous sight faire Britomart amazed,
That all the rest it did amazed make,
Who was so far from being ought amazed,
In which amazement, when the Miscreant
Seemd that lowde thunder with amazement great
With great amazement of so wondrous sight,
With such amazement, that in haste he fled,
Beheld her, all were with amazement smit,
But too and fro in great amazement reel'd,
And found himselfe on ground in great amazement.
With great amazement they were stupefide;
With great amazement, & his thought with wonder fild.
